fields:
Roles of the cell nucleus:

1) {{c1::Contains the code in the form of DNA}}
2) {{c1::Contains machinery for DNA replication and RNA synthesis}}

The nucleas location and shape:

1) Usually located {{c1::near the center of the cell}}...
2) Usually {{c1::spherical::shape?}}...
3) {{c1::One::How many?}} per cell...

1) ...but is sometimes eccentric
2) ...but can be irregular or lobed
3) ...but some cells contain more than one

- similar in composition to cytoplasm
- a gel-like material containing water, proteins, nucleotides and other dissolved substances
The nuclear envelope is made up of two unit membranes, separated by a {{c1::perinuclear}} space
The outer membrane of the nuclear envelope contains ribosomes because it is continuous with {{c1::the rough ER::which organelle?}}
The inner membrane of the nuclear envelope is supported by the {{c1::nuclear lamina}}, which is formed of lamins and associated proteins
There are about {{c1::3000-4000::how many?}} nuclear pores per nucleus
The areas of continuity between the outer and inner nuclear membranes are the {{c1::nuclear pores}}
The NPC ({{c1::define NPC}}) is a {{c2::nuclear pore}} associated with proteins called {{c3::nucleoporins}}
{{c3::Heterochromatin}} is {{c1::dense, clumped::finely dispersed/granular}}, and oftern located at the {{c2::periphery:Location in nucleus}} of the nucleus
{{c1::Euchromatin}} is {{c2::finely dispersed::dense, clumped/finely dispersed}}, granular and is is uncoiled (which means that it is {{c3::actively:actively/not actively}} transcribing.
Nucleosomes are composed of {{c1::8::how many}} histones
The role of the nucleosome is to help {{c1::compact::unpack/compact}} the chromatin.
At the beginning of mitosis, each chromosome is formed of {{c1::2/or sister}} chromatids joined by a centromere.
A {{c1::telomere}} is a region located at the end of a chromosome.
In malignant cells, a {{c1::telomerase}} adds repeated nucleotide sequences to the end of the telomere.
Humans have {{c1::23}} pairs of homologous chromosomes. {{c1::22}} pairs are autosomes while {{c1::1}} pair are sex chromosomes.
All normal human somatic cells contain {{c1::46}} chromosomes.
In {{c1::females::males/females}} one of the X chromosomes is inactivated and can be seen as a mass of condensed chromatin called {{c1::sex chromatin}} or {{c1::Barr body}}

Somatic cells are: 
A. Haploid and have 2n chromosomes
B. Haploid and have n chromosomes
C. Diploid and have 2n chromosomes
D. Diploids and have n chromosomes

What cells are haploid and have half the number of chromosomes of diploids?
A. Somatic cells
B. Germ cells
C. Zygotes
D. Gametes
What is shown in the image?
A {{c1::karyotype}} is a visual image of the complement of chromosomes in a {{c1::metaphase}} cell, arranged according to {{c1::chromosome number}}
The nucleolus is roughtly {{c1::spherical}} in shape and {{c1::does not::does/does not}} have a membrane.
{{c1::T::T/F}} There are sometimes 2 nucleoli in a single nucleus.
The two distinct regions in EM photos of the nucleolus are the {{c1::pars fibrosa and pars granulosa.}}

The nucleolus is composed of three things: 
{{c1::chromatin containing genes for rRNA}}
{{c1::rRNA}}
{{c1::proteins involved with regulating ribosome production}}
RNA polymerase {{c1::1::number}} is involved in transcription of rRNA genes.
How do partially assembled ribosomes exit the nucleus? Where do they finish assembly?
{{c1::Mitosis}} is the division of a somatic cell into two daughter cells containing the same complement of chromosomes.

Reasons for mitosis:
{{c1::Increases}} cell number
{{c1::Renews}} cell populations
Allows for {{c1::wound repair}}

In prophase, chromatin {{c1::condenses::condense/disperse}} to form chomosomes. The cell is {{c1::2n::2n/4n}} and the {{c1:: nucleus::location}} and {{c1::nuclear envelope::location}} disappear. Centrosomes move to {{c1::opposite poles::location}}
In {{c1::metaphase::stage of mitosis}}, microtubules of the {{c1::spindle::structure}} attach to the centromeres of the chromosomes via the {{c1::kinetochore::location on chromosome}}
Where do chromosomes move to line up in metaphase?
In anaphase, {{c1::cohesins}} hold the chromatids together at the centromere, but eventually break down to release the {{c1::sister chromatids}} as they move toward {{c1::opposite poles.::location}}
During telophase, the {{c1::nuclear envelope::cellular structure}} is reformed and chromosomes uncoil into {{c1::chromatin.}}
What is the process of cells cleaving into 2 daughter cells?
The time between one mitosis and the next mitosis is termed the {{c1::cell cycle.}}
G1 phase gathers {{c1::nutrients}} and synthesizes {{c1::RNA}} and {{c1::proteins}} neccesary for DNA synthesis.

The two checkpoints during G1 are:
{{c1::restriction checkpoint}} - monitors cell's size, physiologic state and interactions with ECM.
{{c1::DNA damage checkpoint}} - if this occurs, cell might undergo apoptosis
In {{c1::S}} phase, DNA is replicated and new chromatids are formed. Its one checkpoint is the {{c1::DNA damage checkpoint.}}
In G2 phase, cell {{c1::growth}} and {{c1::reorganization}} of organelles prepares for mitosis.

The two checkpoints of G2 are:
{{c1::DNA damage checkpoint}}
{{c1::Unreplicated DNA checkpoint}} - prevents progression of M phase until completed
The {{c1::G0}} phase represents a halt to the cell cycle and occurs at the {{c1::G1}} phase.

The G0 phase occurs in cells that are:
A. Postmitotic
B. Differentiating
C. Specializing
D. A and C
E. All of the above
{{c1::F::T/F}} If a cell enter the G0 phase, it remains there indefinitely until the cell undergoes apoptosis.
In some cases, the cell can eventually return to G<sub>1</sub>
